In the Heat of Protest¶

Mason Meeks

Since the mid-2010s, it feels as though our world and society has changed a lot, especially with how we engage politically. Using data from the Crowd Counting Consortium, I will be investigating the ebb and flow of protests from 2020 to present day. Specifically, I will be using protest data from July of each year since 2020. The primary reason for using a singular month from each year is that July is directly in the middle of the time of year in which the majority of the year's protests happen. Therefore, the use of one month from each year will not only be simplier, but also give us an insight into further research.

I will also be using hate crime data from the FBI's Crime Data Explorer which will allow me to find correlations and create models to investigate the connection between a particular states's protest-based political affiliation, protest activity, and hate crime frequency. The overall goal of this project is to determine which states see the most per capita hate crimes and protests, and to uderstand if those factors are connected as well as with that state's political affiliation.

The github page for this notebook can be found here

Data Set Number 1¶

This data comes from the Crowd Counting Consortium (found here) which analyzes every protest, demonstration, rally, vigil, etc. throughout the U.S. The creators of this data have coded in many aspects of protests including its location, size, claim, groups, interactions among protesters, interactions among police, and many others. I chose this data because it should give me an abundance of information that will allow me to ask and potentially answer many types of questions. The initial question I hope to investigate with this data is how the frequency of protests and number of protesters have changed since 2020. With major elections, COVID, and massive public responses to policies and governmental actions, I expect to find a lot of interesting statistics that will shape the overall goal of this project.

Data Set Number 2¶

This data comes from the FBI Crime Data Explorer and is a depiction of each of the US states' reported hate crime incidents. The data I am using are the reports from 2020, 2021, and 2022. I would like to clarify that I am not reading in the original data that you would find on the website as that data was poorly formatted for reading into Pandas. Therefore, I copied the data into a new Excel file and formatted it in a way that could be read into Pandas. I also did not copy over extraneous data that I would not be using in this project.

The data can be found under the "Documents and Downloads" section of the front page. Link to data: https://cde.ucr.cjis.gov/LATEST/webapp/#/pages/downloads

Conclusions and Future Analysis¶

It seems as though many of the graphs are slightly spiked around the top-third. Furthermore, the spikes seem relatively consistent throughout the states. THerefore, there might be a trend among a state's protest political affiliation, protest activity, and hate crime frequency. However, for future modeling, I would probably standardize the numbering of the graphs to show percentiles instead of raw numbers. Since a state's population can be drastically different than another's, displaying these statistics in a percentile format could be more intuitively understandable. Further, I would want to break each of the graphs above down by year to see if there are any notable differences between the years.

In terms of future modeling, I have two potential avenues to explore. The first is to attempt to find a statistically positive correlation between a state's hate crime frequency and protest activity. We saw the death of George Floyd spark a massive protest increase in 2020, so I am wondering if lesser known cases have a similar effect. The second is to attempt to find a significant correlation between a state's protest-based political affiliation and their hate crime frequency. That is, do hate crimes generate an increase or decrease in protest frequency for a certain political affiliation? These questions are what I will be trying to answer in the final stage of this project.
